  "caption": "Tokyo tips from a Japanese local 🇯🇵 7 mistakes to avoid when visiting Tokyo, Japan!\n\nFrom shopping, food spots, art and culture, here are my top tips to have in mind when travelling to Tokyo!\n\nFor more local recommendations, my Tokyo guide has over 400 locations! Comment GUIDE and I’ll send you the link ❤️\n\nTokyo travel tips | Tokyo travel guide | Tokyo itinerary | Tokyo things to do | Tokyo recommendations | Tokyo shopping | Tokyo thrifting | Tokyo food spots |",
  "transcript": "Here are seven mistakes to avoid when visiting Tokyo, Japan. Number one, falling victim to overpriced food stores at Tsukiji Aote Market. So generally, Tsukiji Market is a touristy place. The prices are way higher than what locals would pay, but I still think the food is good and worth visiting if it's one of your first times in the city. Some stores are more touristy than others, though, so here are some local favorites for seafood and sushi. And for other great bites, check out these places. By the way, I have a Tokyo guide which lists hundreds of other authentic food gems like these if you want more recommendations. Number two, not familiarizing yourself with Japanese thrift stores before going. Tokyo has one of the best thrift scenes in the world, but if you don't know where to look, you're gonna miss out. For vintage designer, head to Kindle, Second Street, and Ragtag. If you want vintage, but not just designer, check out Bookoff, Kinji, New York Joe's, Flamingo, Treasure Factory, and Bad Store. And for thrifting at actual bargain prices, head to Modolf or Tanpopo House. Number three, skipping Kapabashi Street. When visiting Asakusa, many tourists will head to Sensoji Temple and then leave. But I urge you to walk a few minutes further to explore Tokyo's kitchen town, Kapabashi Street. It's packed with all things kitchenware, from beautiful ceramics to high quality Japanese knives, and even those famous fake food displays. Here are some of my favorite stores to check out in the area. Number four, missing out on Tokyo's garden and green spaces. When you think of Tokyo, you think of neon lights, some bustling streets, but the city has so many beautiful parts, gardens worth checking out. Expect seasonal flowers, koi ponds, and peaceful tea houses. These are some of my favorites that are worth checking out. Number five, ignoring Tokyo's underground food scene. Believe it or not, some of the best meals in the city are hiding in basements, department stores, or even in train stations. For the best department store food floors, check out these for train station gems. Tokyo Station's Ramen Street is home to many restaurants specializing in ramen, and you'll find many hidden food spots from stations like Shibuya and Shinjuku. For underground alleys and basements, check out Yurakshō's Izakaya alleys under the tracks. Number six, only shopping at Don Quixote for souvenirs and goods. A lot of tourists treat Don Quixote as the go-to spot for souvenirs, but there are so many other places worth checking out too. When it comes to beauty products, try these. Book lovers should stop by here. For high quality stationery, check out these. Camera enthusiasts would love these. For Japanese craft goods and for clever homeware and travel goods. And for cute character goods and limited edition toys, check out these. Number seven, only visiting Team Labs as your art fix. While Team Labs' immersive digital art installations are stunning, Tokyo has an incredible variety of museums and galleries beyond it. For contemporary art and design, check out these. For iconic museums, check out these. For traditional and cultural art, check out these. And for hidden gems, check out these. I hope this was helpful and be sure to follow for more Japan and Tokyo tips.",
